04216nam a22007215i 9780801456329DE-B159720180924034856.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180924s2015    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014563297 a10.7591/97808014563292doi  a(DE-B1597)496492  a(OCoLC)1041982083  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB753.F32bE5 2015 7aPHI0120002bisacsh 7aPHI0190002bisacsh 7aPHI0460002bisacsh04a181/.62231 aAlfarabi, eauthor.14aThe Political Writings :b"Political Regime" and "Summary of Plato's Laws" /cAlfarabi. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAgora Editions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPolitical Regime, Nicknamed Principles of the Existents -- tIntroduction -- tThe Text -- tSummary of Plato's Laws -- tIntroduction -- tThe Text -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tGlossary A -- tGlossary B -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aAlfarabi (ca. 870-950) founded the great tradition of Aristotelian/Platonic political philosophy in medieval Islamic and Arabic culture. In this second volume of political writings, Charles E. Butterworth presents translations of Alfarabi's Political Regime and Summary of Plato's "Laws," accompanied by introductions that discuss the background for each work and explore its teaching. In addition, the texts are carefully annotated to aid the reader in following Alfarabi's argument. An Arabic-English/English-Arabic glossary allows interested readers to verify the way particular words are translated. Throughout, Butterworth's method is to translate consistently the same Arabic word by the same English word, rendering Alfarabi's style in an unusually faithful and yet approachable manner.Political Regime consists of two parts. One focuses on nature and natural existing things as well as the principles beyond nature that guide the existing things. In the second part, the exposition centers on human beings and their place in the larger cosmic whole as well as on how a proper organization of human life in political association provides the conditions whereby human beings might achieve their purpose.Summary of Plato's "Laws" gives an account of the first nine books of Plato's Laws. Alfarabi explains Plato's art of writing in general and the method he follows in writing the Laws in particular. Unlike Alfarabi's other works, which examine the place of legislation and laws in the broader context of political philosophy, the Summary is a more specialized study of the question of laws and how and why they are formulated, with a particular focus on the relevance of Plato's investigation concerning Greek divine laws for the study and understanding of all divine laws.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018) 0aIslamic philosophyvEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyvEarly works to 1800.1 aButterworth, Charles E.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801456329423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801456329.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG